07:24.740 --> 07:28.115
Greta, hey, I... I got your
message. Is everything okay?

07:28.170 --> 07:30.451
[ Sighs ]
It's great to have him back.

07:30.498 --> 07:34.600
It is, but, uh, Dr. Werner...
he isn't himself.

07:34.669 --> 07:36.241
Right.

07:37.849 --> 07:42.429
He's had a patient unconscious
in his office for over an hour.

07:42.498 --> 07:44.822
What?

07:47.831 --> 07:51.626
Noah? Noah?

07:51.696 --> 07:53.575
[ Door closes ]

07:56.106 --> 07:58.053
Noah?

07:58.626 --> 08:00.412
Hey, George!

08:00.482 --> 08:02.142
- Whoa.
- Good to see you.

08:02.189 --> 08:04.241
You look well.

08:04.310 --> 08:05.861
Is that a new top?

08:05.893 --> 08:08.861
Noah, w... what's...
what's going on with this guy?

08:09.245 --> 08:12.260
Oh, you know, I can't do this.
I can't do it anymore.

08:12.320 --> 08:13.792
I can't. I tried, and I just can't.

08:13.839 --> 08:15.412
It goes against all my training.

08:15.481 --> 08:17.765
Your... your dental training?

08:17.805 --> 08:19.812
No, my mental-wellness training.

08:19.860 --> 08:21.919
I can't bring myself to brutally

08:21.951 --> 08:23.943
wrench the bone from his flesh.

08:23.990 --> 08:25.311
It's the ripping and the tearing.

08:25.358 --> 08:27.597
It's the rippin' and
the tearin'. I won't do it!

08:27.629 --> 08:30.636
Well, you should have thought of
that before you anesthetized him.

08:30.706 --> 08:33.361
You're not wrong about that.

08:33.417 --> 08:34.715
But you... y... you...

08:34.784 --> 08:36.047
[ Sighs ]

08:36.119 --> 08:37.552
...have great instincts.

08:37.621 --> 08:40.900
You know, and a... and a...
and a... and a steady hand.

08:40.972 --> 08:44.023
You know? Uh, you got a...
you got a firm...

08:44.070 --> 08:45.879
firm... firm grip. Hold it.

08:45.950 --> 08:48.204
I've always said that about you.

08:48.275 --> 08:51.624
Noah, I mean, doesn't that
require years of training?

08:51.694 --> 08:55.146
Not... really.

08:55.214 --> 08:58.086
Just think of it as a nail that
you're pulling out of a wall.

08:58.155 --> 09:01.470
Right? You've pulled plenty
of nails out of walls.

09:01.539 --> 09:04.308
- Noah...
- This one's just made of jawbone.

09:04.377 --> 09:05.743
That one.

09:14.120 --> 09:15.283
[ Groans ]

09:16.581 --> 09:18.322
[ Sighs ]

09:19.164 --> 09:21.684
I could go to jail for what I did today.

09:21.709 --> 09:23.348
This could be my last meal.

09:23.418 --> 09:25.024
In that case, it needs salt.

09:25.093 --> 09:28.238
And the worst part isn't all
the hand-holding Noah needs.

09:28.306 --> 09:31.452
The worst part is feeling
like I... I lost a best friend.

09:31.522 --> 09:33.428
Just as I gain 17 new ones.

09:33.467 --> 09:36.507
George, not to gloat,
but I joined a band.

09:36.554 --> 09:38.491
Well, they're not so much
of a band as they are

09:38.546 --> 09:40.569
a radical musical movement,

09:40.620 --> 09:43.720
and the best part is
they're not from Chatswin.

09:43.776 --> 09:46.010
In fact, they're
the antithesis of Chatswin.

09:46.049 --> 09:47.143
Where are they from?

09:47.211 --> 09:49.638
The whole wide world... planet Earth.

09:49.707 --> 09:55.006
They are musical nomads, and
they taught me how to play...

09:55.076 --> 09:58.287
[ Rattling ]
...this.

10:00.033 --> 10:03.996
- The giant stick?
- The giant rain stick.

10:04.067 --> 10:08.371
It is a conduit for divination,
relaxation,

10:08.443 --> 10:12.474
and spiritual healing.

10:12.546 --> 10:13.979
Cool.

10:14.049 --> 10:16.373
- Can you hear it?
- Yeah.

10:16.442 --> 10:17.563
[ Rattling continues ]

10:17.605 --> 10:21.056
- Can you feel it?
- Eh.

10:21.127 --> 10:23.463
Well, Nimmy says it's transformative.

10:23.502 --> 10:24.863
Yeah, well, maybe Nimmy can use it

10:24.870 --> 10:27.457
to transform Noah back
to the way he used to be.

10:27.512 --> 10:30.084
- Nimmy? I can't be saying that right.
- You are.

10:30.116 --> 10:32.079
It's like Noah overcorrected, you know?

10:32.127 --> 10:34.328
He's... he's completely neutered.

10:34.423 --> 10:36.903
I have to figure out a way
to snap him out of it.

10:36.928 --> 10:39.762
George, I'm telling you, I have the cure

10:39.809 --> 10:42.277
for what ails him
right here in this stick.

10:42.324 --> 10:43.808
- You want me to show you?
- Sure.

10:43.876 --> 10:46.474
Can you muster a little enthusiasm?!

10:48.837 --> 10:50.751
Sure!

10:53.073 --> 10:56.046
[ Rattling ]

10:56.117 --> 10:58.064
[ Exhales sharply ]

10:58.134 --> 11:01.107
[ Rhythmic rattling ]

11:01.174 --> 11:03.671
[ Exhales sharply ]

11:03.894 --> 11:06.175
Right, so, we have that.

11:06.200 --> 11:08.252
Maybe I'll just try
a couple other things...

11:08.321 --> 11:10.158
first.

11:10.221 --> 11:12.613
<i>Since poor food service</i>
<i>was Noah's button...</i>

11:12.682 --> 11:16.680
Well, I... I cannot imagine
what is taking the food so long.

11:16.751 --> 11:19.827
<i>...Dad decided to push it</i>
<i>again and again.</i>

11:19.895 --> 11:22.322
Waiter: First course, gentlemen,
Chef's salad.

11:22.391 --> 11:24.578
Ah.

11:24.648 --> 11:26.664
Dressing on the side?

11:29.806 --> 11:31.412
Oh.

11:36.246 --> 11:38.639
No onions.

11:47.080 --> 11:49.400
You're allergic to onions.

11:49.425 --> 11:51.544
And that's a $23 salad.

11:52.177 --> 11:55.731
Which is why it will not go to waste.

11:59.787 --> 12:01.985
Can I get you anything else?

12:02.015 --> 12:03.485
Hmm.

12:03.554 --> 12:06.049
Maybe just a... a small glass of water.

12:08.661 --> 12:10.637
Coming right...

12:10.701 --> 12:18.085
u-u-u-u-u-u-u-u-u-u-u-u-u-u-p.

12:23.761 --> 12:28.579
Nothing in life is perfect,
not even this glass of water.

12:30.091 --> 12:32.692
Really? You're gonna drink the water?

12:32.762 --> 12:34.436
Oh, geez.

12:40.753 --> 12:43.190
I must say you're looking quite golden.

12:43.245 --> 12:45.569
Quite, quite golden indeed.

12:45.638 --> 12:49.637
Perhaps one or two of you still
need to work on your technique.

12:49.707 --> 12:53.877
Perhaps it's just one of you...
one student in particular.

12:53.947 --> 12:56.321
I know, okay? I know. I dozed off.

12:56.368 --> 12:58.275
Well, that's what
the buddy system is for,

12:58.314 --> 13:01.254
and I can't help but notice
your buddy, Tessa Altman,

13:01.324 --> 13:03.154
is once again a no-show.

13:03.186 --> 13:05.747
No, Tessa's here. She's definitely here.

13:05.818 --> 13:09.989
She just has a... raging U.T.I.

13:10.057 --> 13:13.943
Um, you know how much bacteria...

13:14.020 --> 13:16.664
loves Tessa.

13:16.735 --> 13:19.813
Um, you know what?
She's probably in the bathroom.

13:19.860 --> 13:23.244
- I'll just go check.
- Okay.

13:23.313 --> 13:24.919
Hey!

13:24.989 --> 13:27.354
- Buddy, what gives?!
- Oh.

13:27.401 --> 13:29.921
[ Grunts ]
I just had to cover for you again.

13:31.746 --> 13:32.974
What are those dots?

13:33.043 --> 13:35.180
- Never mind my dots.
- Now you have dots?

13:35.227 --> 13:36.438
Okay, okay.

13:36.501 --> 13:38.615
I found something way more enriching

13:38.670 --> 13:40.927
than the march towards skin cancer.

13:40.995 --> 13:47.483
I joined a band,
and it's amazing and liberating.

13:47.545 --> 13:50.192
And I really hope you come see
us play in the park.

13:50.260 --> 13:51.627
Why do you look like "Braveheart"?

13:51.696 --> 13:55.285
Why? Because my buddy
has her priorities screwed up.

13:55.355 --> 13:58.020
[ Scoffs ]
My priorities are screwed up?

13:58.090 --> 13:59.388
You can't keep skipping class.

13:59.457 --> 14:02.260
- Lisa, it's not a real class.
- It will be when you fail it.

14:02.329 --> 14:05.081
Lisa... if you want to
be a half-tan sheep

14:05.113 --> 14:07.060
in a full-tan flock, go for it.

14:07.129 --> 14:08.940
But me, I'm marching to the beat

14:08.968 --> 14:11.598
of a different drummer... Luke.

14:12.572 --> 14:14.816
- That's my band's drummer.
- You're still in a flock.

14:14.863 --> 14:16.690
It's just a different flock,

14:16.759 --> 14:18.160
and I can't believe you'd be more loyal

14:18.231 --> 14:20.486
to a group of strangers
you just met in the park

14:20.554 --> 14:22.023
than you would be to me,
your best friend!

14:22.092 --> 14:23.693
What am I supposed to do about a buddy?!

14:23.733 --> 14:26.230
I don't know, Lisa.

14:27.222 --> 14:30.297
Maybe it's time you go
find yourself a new one.

14:33.820 --> 14:35.084
[ Rattling ]

14:35.479 --> 14:37.497
Burn.

14:37.875 --> 14:39.836
On your face.

14:39.904 --> 14:43.152
You should get that looked at.

14:43.986 --> 14:45.739
[ Knock on glass ]

14:48.386 --> 14:49.716
Yeah, what about?

14:49.785 --> 14:51.015
Oh!

14:51.084 --> 14:53.032
I don't know why I thought
it was soundproof.

14:53.102 --> 14:55.187
It looked soundproof, but it isn't.

14:55.254 --> 14:56.827
It's about Tessa.

14:57.222 --> 14:58.855
[ Sighs ]
What's up, Dallas?

14:58.894 --> 15:00.799
Well, this is about
the bronzing requirement

15:00.838 --> 15:02.990
expected from all students
in their senior year.

15:03.364 --> 15:06.439
Tessa's performance, I'm afraid,
pales in comparison,

15:06.510 --> 15:07.841
and I just wanted to...

15:07.910 --> 15:09.630
Wanted to come down
and talk to me about it.

15:09.946 --> 15:13.001
- Got it.
- Well, now, hold on. Am I detecting a tone?

15:13.056 --> 15:13.978
No, no tone.

15:14.046 --> 15:15.686
I will talk to Tessa

15:15.756 --> 15:18.490
about taking her "tanning class"
more seriously.

15:18.559 --> 15:20.337
And the next time
you want to talk to me,

15:20.406 --> 15:22.782
don't feel compelled to use
my daughter as an excuse.

15:22.852 --> 15:23.808
What?!

15:23.879 --> 15:26.346
First off, if you're implying

15:26.377 --> 15:28.290
that I harbor tenderness for you,

15:28.360 --> 15:29.693
you are sorely mistaken.

15:29.761 --> 15:32.189
And secondly, I don't appreciate
your "air quotes"

15:32.256 --> 15:34.239
and "all" that they "imply."

15:34.309 --> 15:37.556
- Incorrect use of air quotes.
- Incorrect use of your mama.

15:37.625 --> 15:40.051
I came down here
out of concern for Tessa.

15:40.120 --> 15:41.481
And if you're not concerned, well,

15:41.488 --> 15:44.084
there's nothing for you
to concern yourself with.

15:48.360 --> 15:50.444
[ Mid-tempo music plays ]

15:50.513 --> 15:53.658
♪ There you go, mm-mm-mm ♪

15:54.584 --> 15:55.984
♪ Ooh, yeah ♪

15:56.053 --> 15:58.239
Hang on, guys. Hang on a sec.

15:58.310 --> 16:01.200
Tessa, everything okay?

16:01.240 --> 16:02.539
Yeah. Why?

16:02.608 --> 16:05.206
The stick felt a little off today.

16:05.275 --> 16:07.188
- A lot off.
- Shut up, Nonny.

16:07.228 --> 16:08.748
Why don't you mind your own washboard?

16:08.767 --> 16:12.173
Whoa, hey. Whoa. Not cool.

16:12.228 --> 16:15.511
Tessa, i... if something
is intruding on your happiness,

16:15.579 --> 16:20.125
let us know, but please
don't intrude on Nonny's.

16:20.195 --> 16:23.271
Sorry... Nonny.

16:23.340 --> 16:25.594
Sorry, you guys.

16:25.665 --> 16:29.288
I just, um... I got in
an argument with my best friend,

16:29.357 --> 16:32.332
and I know she's really mad at me.

16:32.399 --> 16:35.681
And I guess it's really nagging at me.

16:35.751 --> 16:38.191
[ Sighs ]
Would it help if we killed her?

16:39.544 --> 16:41.693
What?

16:41.733 --> 16:43.372
If we murdered her, I mean.

16:43.443 --> 16:46.518
You see, technically, the band
is your best friend now,

16:46.587 --> 16:49.049
and we find
that outside friendships tend

16:49.118 --> 16:51.282
to get really problematic.

16:51.337 --> 16:53.853
So killing, uh...

16:53.907 --> 16:55.306
Lisa.

16:55.345 --> 16:59.038
...Lisa might be the cleanest
way to go on this one.

16:59.649 --> 17:02.765
<i>A charismatic leader,</i>
<i>no outside friendships,</i>

17:02.833 --> 17:05.034
<i>matching white outfits,</i>
<i>and made-up names</i>

17:05.055 --> 17:07.277
<i>that rhyme with the exception of Luke.</i>

17:07.348 --> 17:10.627
<i>How could I have missed it?</i>
<i>I didn't join a band.</i>

17:10.696 --> 17:12.916
<i>I joined a cult!</i>

17:19.768 --> 17:21.307
[ Laughter ]

17:21.377 --> 17:22.963
Um...

17:23.010 --> 17:26.088
Caris, I just had,
like, a small question

17:26.142 --> 17:30.920
that I wanted to
question you about over here.

17:30.990 --> 17:32.037
Shoot.

17:32.100 --> 17:35.637
So, uh, what happens to band members

17:35.684 --> 17:37.402
who don't want to
be in the band anymore.

17:37.434 --> 17:40.987
[ Laughs ] Tessa, we don't keep
people here by force, silly.

17:41.042 --> 17:43.174
You can pretty much go anytime you want.

17:43.222 --> 17:45.204
You just need to turn your uniform in,

17:45.274 --> 17:48.486
suffer one exit beating,
and you are on your way.

17:48.879 --> 17:50.598
Exit b... beating?

17:50.661 --> 17:52.292
Oh, it's a formality.

17:52.363 --> 17:55.846
Exit beatings are exacted using
whichever instrument you play.

17:55.918 --> 17:58.481
In your case... youch!

17:58.518 --> 17:59.770
Yeah.

17:59.833 --> 18:01.528
Too bad I don't play the kazoo, right?

18:01.583 --> 18:02.916
[ Laughing ]
Yeah.

18:02.986 --> 18:06.717
But I once took someone's eye
out with one of those, so...

18:08.081 --> 18:09.379
Right.

18:09.447 --> 18:10.970
[ Laughs ]
Hey.

18:11.415 --> 18:13.542
You're not thinking
about leaving, are you?

18:13.605 --> 18:15.758
- No way.
- Okay.

18:18.231 --> 18:20.377
Lisa: Tessa? Tessa?

18:20.440 --> 18:21.931
Lisa, no. No, no, no, no.

18:21.979 --> 18:23.210
You have to get out of here.

18:23.242 --> 18:24.368
Look, I know that things got pretty real

18:24.398 --> 18:25.632
in the bathroom between us.

18:25.671 --> 18:27.202
- What? What are you talking about?
- The fight.

18:27.257 --> 18:28.338
But I just want you to know

18:28.365 --> 18:30.142
that I put our friendship
above all else.

18:30.211 --> 18:32.535
So if Muhammad won't tan
at the mountain...

18:32.604 --> 18:35.371
the mountain will play
in the band with Muhammad.

18:35.442 --> 18:37.696
Lisa, this is a cult,
and they're gonna kill you.

18:37.767 --> 18:40.602
They're gonna kill you. They
told me they want to kill you.

18:40.674 --> 18:43.189
- Mm, what?
- Yeah.

18:43.423 --> 18:44.556
Dallas: Look here!

18:44.611 --> 18:47.402
Not one but two little cutters
who avoided my...

18:48.293 --> 18:50.394
Holy crap!

18:50.434 --> 18:52.542
This is a cult. You girls joined a cult?

18:52.597 --> 18:53.689
Unintentionally.

18:53.759 --> 18:55.199
H... how did you even know that this...

18:55.263 --> 18:58.093
Oh, my gosh, I was big
into cults as a tween.

18:58.152 --> 19:00.304
Loved cults, loved 'em.

19:00.376 --> 19:02.231
If not for all those pesky
exit beatings...

19:02.278 --> 19:03.575
I don't want an exit beating.

19:03.646 --> 19:04.944
Okay, girls, just take a deep breath.

19:05.011 --> 19:07.405
I'm gonna ask you a few questions.
[ Exhales deeply ]

19:07.475 --> 19:10.462
- How many have you slept with?
- What?! None!

19:10.510 --> 19:11.943
And you haven't exchanged any vows

19:12.013 --> 19:13.961
or sister-wived yourself in any way?

19:14.029 --> 19:15.841
- No.
- Good. You're doing great.

19:15.912 --> 19:18.405
Do they know your last name,
your place of residence,

19:18.474 --> 19:20.080
or either of your socials?

19:20.150 --> 19:21.105
- No!
- No!

19:21.176 --> 19:24.148
In that case... run!

19:27.569 --> 19:29.732
- Oh, damn!
- Lisa!

19:29.757 --> 19:31.055
Don't slow down!

19:31.124 --> 19:33.724
If she's supposed to make it, she will!

19:34.953 --> 19:36.950
George: She said it was a band.

19:37.013 --> 19:38.825
Well, there was a musical element.

19:38.894 --> 19:41.559
But then with most good cults,
there usually is.

19:41.629 --> 19:43.179
I'm sorry I didn't take you seriously.

19:43.219 --> 19:45.507
I can't thank you enough
for looking out for Tessa.

19:45.578 --> 19:47.558
You want to stay, have a slice of pizza?

19:47.628 --> 19:49.860
- It's the least I can do.
- No, thanks.

19:50.118 --> 19:53.362
Um, but, George, the next time
you want to invite me to dinner,

19:53.402 --> 19:56.440
you don't need to use
your "daughter" as an excuse.

19:56.488 --> 19:59.358
Improper use of air quotes.
She is my daughter.

19:59.428 --> 20:00.897
[ Laughs ]

20:01.194 --> 20:02.661
<i>When friendships change,</i>

20:02.700 --> 20:05.389
<i>sometimes you have to change with them.</i>

20:05.555 --> 20:08.502
<i>Lisa was willing to join a cult</i>
<i>to save our friendship,</i>

20:08.558 --> 20:10.337
<i>so maybe George had given up too quickly</i>

20:10.405 --> 20:11.885
<i>on connecting with Noah.</i>

20:11.933 --> 20:15.281
<i>After all,</i>
<i>he was Simon to his Garfunkel.</i>

20:15.352 --> 20:18.466
Both: ♪ Old friends ♪

20:19.968 --> 20:23.872
♪ Old friends ♪

20:24.753 --> 20:28.648
♪ Sat on a park bench like bookends ♪

20:30.675 --> 20:34.535
♪ A newspaper blows through the grass ♪

20:34.607 --> 20:37.785
♪ Falls on the round toes ♪

20:37.854 --> 20:40.075
♪ Of the high shoes ♪

20:40.146 --> 20:44.196
♪ Of the old friends ♪

20:45.289 --> 20:47.289
Thank you, George.

20:47.797 --> 20:50.896
- I know I let you down.
- No, no.

20:50.959 --> 20:53.033
I let you down.

20:53.101 --> 20:56.421
For not being more... accepting.

20:57.719 --> 21:00.061
But that's all behind us now.

21:00.124 --> 21:01.253
[ Sighs ]

21:01.320 --> 21:03.473
I just have never been so...

21:03.543 --> 21:08.841
at peace in my life...
My son playing in the sand...

21:08.912 --> 21:11.567
best friend at my side.

21:12.793 --> 21:15.332
Give me that, fat ass!

21:15.694 --> 21:17.505
[ Laughing ]
Whoa!

21:17.574 --> 21:20.581
Wow, that... oh.

21:20.652 --> 21:21.951
[ Chuckles ]

21:22.019 --> 21:24.581
- The old me would have gotten mad at that.
- Right?

21:24.636 --> 21:26.815
- He called my son a "fat ass"!
- You okay?

21:26.871 --> 21:28.509
Well, no, I'm... I... I'm good.

21:28.578 --> 21:30.117
Hoo. Hoo.

21:30.185 --> 21:32.080
- That's right.
- He called him a "fat ass"!

21:32.111 --> 21:33.767
- Hey, hey, Noah! Noah!
- Listen, hey, hey, hey!

21:33.807 --> 21:35.423
I want to... I want to
talk to you there, champ!

21:35.471 --> 21:38.251
- That's not a fat ass! That is a diaper...
a diaper, okay?! - Hey.

21:38.290 --> 21:40.325
<i>Even though George feared for
that child's safety,</i>

21:40.365 --> 21:42.109
<i>he had to admit it was nice</i>

21:42.179 --> 21:43.648
<i>to have his old friend back.</i>

21:43.717 --> 21:45.558
- I will end... you!
- Okay. Okay.

21:45.596 --> 21:46.836
[ Laughing ]
All right?!

